 reconstructing their lives in El Salvador. In focusing on the case of Salvadoran youth, Coutin's nuanced analysis shows how the violence associated with migration can be countered through practices that recuperate historical memory while also reclaiming national membership.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aRefugeeszUnited States. 0aSalvadoran AmericanszUnited States. 0aSalvadoransxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aSalvadoransxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aSalvadoranszUnited States. 0aUnaccompanied immigrant childrenzUnited States. 4aInclusive Excellence Award Winner. 4aUC Irvine Book Awards. 4aUC Irvine Social Ecology Deans Inclusive Excellence Award for Research. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374176zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374176.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles